Comment (src/views/lineage/LineageGraphView.vue:81):
**Low — `selectNode` can interleave under rapid clicks.** It sets `selectedKey`/slices columns synchronously, then `await`s `fetchChildNodes`. Two quick box-clicks (A then B in the same column) can resolve out of order: A's children get pushed after B's `selectedKey` is set, leaving a stale extra column and connector arrows pointing at the wrong box.

A per-invocation token (capture the selected key/column and ignore the push if the selection changed by the time children resolve) would harden it. Cosmetic and PoC-only — non-blocking.
Replies:
**lisa implementation guidance:** Fix in src/views/lineage/LineageGraphView.vue selectNode(). Guard the async children push against out-of-order resolution. Before the await, capture the selection identity: `const token = node.key;` (and colIndex). After `await fetchChildNodes(...)`, bail if the selection changed while awaiting: `if (columns.value[colIndex]?.selectedKey !== token) return;` before columns.value.push(...). This prevents A's children being appended after B was selected. Leave the synchronous selectedKey/slice as-is. Also apply the same guard nothing-after-return for computeArrows so a stale invocation doesn't recompute arrows for a superseded tree.

